### Scope Contract 4: Sticky Anchor Nav

**UX Slice**
- Nav hidden while hero is visible
- Nav appears after hero scrolls out of view
- Active section highlighted while scrolling
- Clicking a pill smooth-scrolls to that section; section title fully visible below nav
- Mobile: pill row scrollable horizontally; active pill auto-scrolls into view

**Architecture Slice**
- `StickyNav.astro`: `position: sticky; top: 0; z-index: 10`
- Skip link at very top of page: `<a href="#main-content" class="sr-only focus:not-sr-only">Skip to main content</a>`
- IntersectionObserver on `#hero`: when hero leaves viewport → add `nav-visible` class to show nav; when re-enters → remove it
- IntersectionObserver on sections 2–14 (`threshold: 0.1`): on intersection, set `aria-current="true"` on matching pill, remove from others
- Nav pill list: 13 pills for sections 2–14 (hero excluded) + one `↑` pill that scrolls to `#hero`
- Each pill: `<button type="button">` inside nav; click handler reads `data-target` attribute (e.g. `"#overview"`), calls `document.querySelector(data-target).scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth' })`
- Note: use `data-target` attribute on buttons (not `href` on anchors) to avoid any ClientRouter interception entirely
- Mobile nav container: `overflow-x: auto; white-space: nowrap` (Tailwind: `overflow-x-auto whitespace-nowrap`)
- Mobile active pill auto-scroll: in IntersectionObserver callback, call `activePillElement.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth', inline: 'center', block: 'nearest' })`
- Mobile back-to-top: fixed `48×48px` button bottom-right, appears after scrolling past hero, scrolls to `#hero` on click
- All observer instances stored in an array; all disconnected on `astro:before-swap`

**Human Verification Checklist**
- [ ] Nav hidden when hero is fully visible
- [ ] Nav appears after scrolling past hero
- [ ] Clicking a pill scrolls to correct section; section title fully visible below nav (not hidden behind it)
- [ ] Active section pill highlighted while scrolling; `aria-current="true"` set (DevTools accessibility tree)
- [ ] Mobile: nav row scrollable horizontally; active pill auto-scrolls into center of row
- [ ] `↑` pill scrolls to top of page
- [ ] Mobile: fixed back-to-top button (48×48px) appears and works
- [ ] Skip link visible on first Tab press, jumps to `#main-content`
- [ ] Navigate away and back → observers do not stack (DevTools Performance — no duplicate callbacks)

---

### Scope Contract 5: Scroll Reveal Animation + Accessibility

**UX Slice**
- Sections 2–14 start visible (opacity 1) when JS is disabled
- When JS is enabled: sections 2–14 start hidden and fade in + slide up as user scrolls to them
- Reduced motion enabled → sections immediately visible, no animation

**Architecture Slice**
- Initial CSS for all `<section>` elements (except `#hero`): `opacity: 1; transform: none; transition: none` — visible by default
- JS (runs on `astro:page-load`): before starting observers, add class `js-reveal-pending` to sections 2–14; CSS for this class: `opacity: 0; transform: translateY(24px); transition: opacity 0.5s ease, transform 0.5s ease`
- `prefers-reduced-motion` check: if true, do not add `js-reveal-pending` class and do not start reveal observers — sections stay visible
- IntersectionObserver at `threshold: 0.1`: when section intersects, remove `js-reveal-pending` class (triggers CSS transition to opacity 1, translateY 0), then call `observer.unobserve(entry.target)` so it fires once only
- Applied to sections 2–14 (not hero, not footer)
- Reveal observers disconnected on `astro:before-swap`

**Human Verification Checklist**
- [ ] JS disabled (DevTools → block JS) → all sections immediately visible; no invisible content
- [ ] JS enabled, scroll down → sections fade in and slide up as they enter viewport
- [ ] Each section reveals once (does not repeat on scroll up and back down)
- [ ] Enable OS reduced motion → all sections immediately visible, no animation even with JS
- [ ] No layout shift from hidden-to-visible transition
- [ ] Works on mobile

## Continuous Verification

- After each scope contract: run `astro dev`, verify checklist
- After scope 5: scroll entire page end-to-end on desktop and mobile emulation
- Check for observer leaks: navigate to case study, away, back — DevTools Performance should show no stacking

## Simplicity Guardrails

- Is sticky nav the simplest possible? (Yes: CSS sticky + two IntersectionObservers + data-target buttons)
- Is scroll reveal the simplest possible? (Yes: single CSS class toggle + one observer per section)
- Are 14 sections manageable? (Yes: single page file, one reusable FeatureSection component)
- Is the JS-disabled fallback simple? (Yes: default CSS is visible; JS opt-in to hidden state)
